data.content:
## What Breaks in .NET 11

In .NET 10, the Cosmos DB provider let you opt into **sync-over-async** (blocking on async calls under the hood). In **.NET 11 (EF Core 11), that opt-in is removed entirely**. All synchronous LINQ operators (`ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`) and `SaveChanges()` on the Cosmos provider now throw `InvalidOperationException` — there's no configuration to suppress it.

### The Fix

Convert every synchronous call to its async counterpart:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

### Key changes

| Sync (broken in .NET 11) | Async replacement |
|---|---|
| `ToList()` | `await ToListAsync()` |
| `First()` | `await FirstAsync()` |
| `Count()` | `await CountAsync()` |
| `SaveChanges()` | `await SaveChangesAsync()` |

You'll also need to propagate `async`/`await` up through every caller in the chain (controllers, services, etc.). The `Add()` call remains synchronous — it only tracks the entity in the change tracker and doesn't hit Cosmos.
